aren't able to get the servers that they need. So today, I want to share some best practices for

00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:06.880
managing RStudio in production. I want to share the product requirements, go over some tips,

00:05:06.880 --> 00:05:10.720
and give you a path for getting started. My goal is to give you a big picture view

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:13.920
of what success looks like, assuming you're using our products.

00:05:14.799 --> 00:05:20.079
So I want to share five best practices for administering RStudio in production.

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:29.440
Number one, keep your system up to date. So you're going to want modern tools for your data science

00:05:29.440 --> 00:05:34.399
platform. That means modern operating systems and modern browsers. You'll be using the cutting

00:05:34.399 --> 00:05:39.119
edge tools, you'll be doing cutting edge analysis, you'll be hiring people with very

00:05:39.279 --> 00:05:43.760
important skills, and you're going to want modern tools for all of those things.

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:49.679
You'll need a C++11 compiler so that you can build the R packages on your system,

00:05:49.679 --> 00:05:53.440
and you'll want to think about your internet access, and that's because all of your packages

00:05:53.440 --> 00:06:00.079
are coming from the internet. If you don't have internet access in your server environment,

00:06:00.079 --> 00:06:03.839
a lot of organizations don't, then it's very important that you talk to RStudio because

00:06:03.920 --> 00:06:06.959
all of our products are designed to run in an offline mode.

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:14.799
Number two, support multiple versions of R. Why do you want to support multiple versions of R?

00:06:14.799 --> 00:06:18.640
Well, because you want to be able to manage upgrades. You want to be able to test code

00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:22.799
on a variety of R versions, and you want to support projects that depend on various versions

00:06:22.799 --> 00:06:30.480
of R. All of our products support multiple versions of R. So you want to be able to

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:37.279
support multiple versions of R. We recommend that you upgrade at least yearly and that you

00:06:37.279 --> 00:06:42.880
use a modern version of R, so 3.1 or greater. And then finally, this is very important that

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:47.440
we recommend that you build R from source. Building R from source allows you to install

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:52.720
multiple versions of R side by side. It's not hard to do. It follows the standard config

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:59.200
make install path. Most organizations have a process for building software from source

00:06:59.200 --> 00:07:02.079
already in place, and we have instructions for how to do that.

00:07:05.359 --> 00:07:11.760
Number three, organize your R packages. So R packages rule the nest. Packages will drive

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:17.760
your R version, your Linux dependencies, and even your operating system. Data scientists will want

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:22.640
to access their most beloved packages. So say you have a data scientist who wants the most recent

00:07:23.279 --> 00:07:28.640
modeling package, and they try to install it, and it fails because it needs a new version of R.

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:32.640
So you want to upgrade that version of R, and then you find that you're going to need some

00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:36.480
Linux binaries, but those Linux binaries aren't really supported by your operating system. So

00:07:36.480 --> 00:07:40.239
suddenly you're upgrading your whole operating system to support that package of R. That is not

00:07:40.239 --> 00:07:44.959
an unrealistic scenario. That's one reason we say keep your platform modern and up to date.

00:07:45.760 --> 00:07:51.839
So it turns out that managing packages for a single user is quite easy, like you do on your

00:07:51.839 --> 00:07:56.959
desktop, but managing packages for an entire platform is really hard. And we should know,

00:07:56.959 --> 00:08:02.480
RStudio knows a lot about managing packages. So we created a package manager. It's called the

00:08:02.480 --> 00:08:07.920
RStudio Package Manager, and it solves several problems. One problem is when your environment

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:12.880
is disconnected from the internet or you're in an air-gapped environment, you need a way to get

00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:17.200
packages into that environment, and Package Manager can help with that. Another one is being

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:22.480
able to serve consistent environments to Docker containers. So if your Docker container is running

00:08:22.959 --> 00:08:27.600
one environment, it's probably not the same environment that you're building on,

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:32.880
but the Package Manager can help standardize those environments. There's also security control

00:08:33.440 --> 00:08:40.320
for package repositories. A lot of organizations like to curate the packages that

00:08:40.320 --> 00:08:46.159
gets delivered to their organization, and then also Package Manager helps with sharing internal

00:08:46.159 --> 00:08:52.159
packages. So since Package Manager is brand new, I thought I'd run through a quick demo of how it

00:08:52.159 --> 00:09:03.919
works. This is the RStudio Package Manager, and it has this nice UI so people can log in and

00:09:04.719 --> 00:09:10.080
see all the packages that are available to them. And in this case, these are my packages. This is

00:09:10.080 --> 00:09:16.719
my description. I can see how often my packages are being updated here. So in this case, these

00:09:17.280 --> 00:09:24.880
packages were updated on March 17th, and 179 packages were added, and 159 packages were

00:09:24.880 --> 00:09:31.760
archived. You can see the alpha-sim-r package here was archived in version 0.9 because it was

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:38.880
upgraded to version 0.10. Now all the packages in this snapshot are indexed with this identifier

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:45.679
1303. If I want to see all of the in all of the snapshots, I can look at this calendar function

00:09:45.679 --> 00:09:50.960
and see the history of when my packages were updated. So my most recent version was March

00:09:50.960 --> 00:09:59.280
17th, and here I can see this is the specific snapshot 1303 that indexes that specific set

00:09:59.280 --> 00:10:06.080
of packages. I can copy that URL, and I can paste it into my IDE, and that means that everything that

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:12.880
all the packages I pull from then on in the IDE are going to pull from a very specific set of

00:10:12.880 --> 00:10:22.960
packages. Then I can take that URL, the package repository location, and put that in my Docker

00:10:22.960 --> 00:10:28.159
container when I spin up the container, and it will pull the same packages I use for my analysis.

00:10:28.159 --> 00:10:32.159
We call this a shared baseline so that everyone is going to be using the same

00:10:33.200 --> 00:10:41.520
packages that are pegged to this checkpoint. In addition to the indexing the packages,

00:10:41.520 --> 00:10:46.400
I can also organize multiple repositories. So here you see I have a repository that consists

00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:54.479
just of validated packages for my group. This repository has packages that were contributed

00:10:54.479 --> 00:10:59.440
internally from my organization, and this repository has packages that are being pulled

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:05.919
down from GitHub. So what this does is what my package manager allows me to do is pull down

00:11:05.919 --> 00:11:11.039
packages from GitHub and compile them or build them locally so that I can have the most up-to-date

00:11:11.039 --> 00:11:19.679
packages. I can also see the usage stats for my packages, which is nice. I can see which

00:11:19.679 --> 00:11:25.280
packages are being downloaded and which licenses are being used. So package manager is really

00:11:25.280 --> 00:11:30.159
valuable to organizations who are standardizing on R. We hope you'll give that a consideration.

00:11:30.799 --> 00:11:33.039
We'll be coming back and visiting that in a little bit.

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:43.440
All right, so number four, use root privileges. So the group in your organization that installs,

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:50.960
configures, and manages R in RStudio will need root privileges. So RStudio installs,

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:58.320
RStudio installs require root privileges, and RStudio products also run as root.

00:11:58.559 --> 00:12:05.119
RStudio Server Pro runs as the root user in order to create a new R session on behalf of its users,

00:12:05.679 --> 00:12:10.880
and RStudio Connect runs as a root user in order to isolate applications and processes.

00:12:10.880 --> 00:12:18.960
I'll also add that system-wide installations of R on Linux oftentimes involve root as well.

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:25.119
So this is very important that the people that have the permissions in your system to install R

00:12:25.760 --> 00:12:34.159
are able to do so effectively. So that means if that person is you,

00:12:34.880 --> 00:12:39.440
then you need to know how to install the products and the software

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:45.760
sufficiently on that system. If that person is someone else, then you need to help that

00:12:45.760 --> 00:12:51.440
person understand what this process involves. That means installing R, the R packages,

00:12:51.440 --> 00:12:56.960
and the products. So the root user privileges, you may or may not have that, but whoever does

00:12:56.960 --> 00:13:01.599
have that needs to have that understanding of what it means to support a platform on R.

00:13:03.440 --> 00:13:08.479
Okay, and the last one, five, is securely manage your users. There's two types of users. There's

00:13:08.479 --> 00:13:13.919
R programmers and there's end users, and the R programmers will need access to R file shares,

00:13:13.919 --> 00:13:20.559
databases, and probably many other sensitive systems. R processes for the R programmers run

00:13:20.640 --> 00:13:29.119
as the user under a local account. So users need local accounts on the system to be running

00:13:29.119 --> 00:13:35.760
these types of analyses. End users, on the other hand, are people that may or may not know R and

00:13:35.760 --> 00:13:41.520
just consume apps and reports. For these, the R processes typically run under a service account.

00:13:41.520 --> 00:13:47.280
And if you look at our two products, you'll see that RStudio Server Pro is serving R programmers

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:54.000
and RStudio Connect is serving end users. The way you configure R studio or R programmers and

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:00.559
end users are probably going to be slightly different experiences, and those systems will

00:14:00.559 --> 00:14:06.000
be slightly different as well. So how do you hook those up? Well, that's where authentication comes

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:12.640
in. Your organization probably has strong opinions on how to authenticate users. This space is only

00:14:12.640 --> 00:14:17.760
getting more fragmented, not less. So if you look at like a lot of on-prem solutions today, we'll

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:25.359
have like LDAP, Active Directory, and then a lot of the web technologies, the cloud technologies

00:14:25.359 --> 00:14:32.320
have things like Okta, Duo, and Auth, and Ping, and Shibboleth, and many, many more. So we want to

00:14:32.320 --> 00:14:36.400
support as many systems as possible to work with your authentication system, and we're working hard

00:14:36.400 --> 00:14:43.359
to do that. And then you will go ahead and configure RStudio with whatever authentication

00:14:43.359 --> 00:14:51.359
system that your organization has. Now, if our products don't support your particular authentication

00:14:51.359 --> 00:14:57.440
system, then we recommend using Proxied Auth. In Proxied Auth, users don't log in through RStudio,

00:14:57.440 --> 00:15:03.119
they actually log through a proxy that you set up, and all this is in the guides. The supported

00:15:03.119 --> 00:15:09.119
Auth methods for RStudio Server Pro are PAM, pretty much, and RStudio Connect. The supported

00:15:09.119 --> 00:15:15.760
Auth methods are typically LDAP, Active Directory, or PAM, and SAML, which is coming up

00:15:15.760 --> 00:15:21.039
soon. So we're working on SAML. Finally, I want to mention Kerberos, which is an authentication.

00:15:21.039 --> 00:15:26.320
It's access control, but use Kerberos to connect to databases, and those are supported by our

00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:31.520
drivers. Our professional drivers allow you to connect to databases using ODBC.

00:15:34.239 --> 00:15:41.119
All right, so in summary, here's my recommendations. Number one, keep your operating systems and

00:15:41.119 --> 00:15:47.039
browsers up to date. Number two, plan to support multiple versions of R by building R from source.

00:15:47.039 --> 00:15:51.840
Number three, organize your R packages for reliability and consistency. Number four,

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:56.960
use root privileges to install and run RStudio products. And number five, securely manage your

00:15:56.960 --> 00:16:04.159
R programmers and end users. So if you stay to these five things as you architect and execute

00:16:04.159 --> 00:16:10.799
your R platform, you will have a lot more success. And there's some information, so we've written up

00:16:10.799 --> 00:16:16.719
some information about how to do this online as well. If you come to this page, you can see

00:16:16.719 --> 00:16:21.200
you've got professional product requirements, and I go through all the professional product

00:16:21.200 --> 00:16:33.520
requirements here. All right, so now that we have like a path for success, what does it look like to

00:16:33.520 --> 00:16:41.919
get started? So the first thing is to get the right tools. RStudio makes tools that you put together.

00:16:41.919 --> 00:16:45.520
There are many ways to assemble R tools, but it's going to be up to you to decide how to put them

00:16:45.520 --> 00:16:50.159
together. Your configuration depends on what data science means to your organization. Our goal is

00:16:50.159 --> 00:16:56.239
to make it as easy to install and configure all of our products. So your solutions might look like

00:16:56.239 --> 00:17:02.000
a data science lab where all your data scientists work together. Maybe you're building

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:07.680
applications in a DevTest prod framework that you're trying to orchestrate and deliver to end

00:17:07.680 --> 00:17:13.520
users. You could be on-premises or on a cloud or a hybrid cloud. You could have a single server or

00:17:13.520 --> 00:17:19.199
multi-departmental deployments, depending on how large your organization is. No matter what you're

00:17:19.199 --> 00:17:24.000
doing, I typically recommend thinking about a crawl-walk-run strategy, where you think about

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:28.400
what the platform is going to look like long-term, and then you start with crawl and walk. I see a lot

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:34.880
of organizations doing that, and I think that's a fine strategy. So this is what a setup might look

00:17:34.880 --> 00:17:44.479
like for you. You might have RStudio develop for your development platform and will connect

00:17:44.479 --> 00:17:50.000
to your projects and your home file shares. Your RStudio Connect will be your publishing

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:56.400
platform and will connect to your file share and your metadata, and then your package manager

